<font color="#FF0000">PTSD/VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 17 18:30:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I fight the Vietnam War every day and night. I have been in treatment for two and a half years. I have attended two residential treatment programs, Roseburg oregon and Vancouver Washington. I realize there is no magic pill to help me but still seek a lot of answers that don't seem to be there. I can remember in Vietnam there were some kids that lived near the wire and we gave them candy and food, one night during incoming I saw them throwing grenades at us, I shot and killed three of them. This is the sort of madness that was to continue during my tour of duty in Vietnam. I was older than the run of the mill Maring when I got to Vietnam, I alread had twelve years of training and thought I had all the answers. I was there only 12 days when three of my crewmen were killed. I was unable to save them and barely save myself. I didn't have the answers and still can't find the answers.<br><br>
The Psychiatrist and treatment workers tell me not to blame myself for what happened over there. How is one to not blame himself, just convince myself that it was all a bad dream? I have had too many bad dreams since then and still have to continue to fight the war. No one can tell me how to get rid of the flashbacks, intrusive thoughts, insolation, and all the other things that has happened to me. I have read several different books and they all say the same thing, DON'T BLAME YOURSELF, that's easy for them to say.
<p><code>-- jclark@empnet.com  (Jerry Clark) </code><p>


